          "body": "Between the retrospective praise of vv. 1-6 and the prophetic confidence of vv. 8-12 stands a single verse that is the psalm's theological center: 'For the king trusts in the LORD, and through the lovingkindness of the Most High he will not be shaken.' Two reasons are given for the king's unshakeable stability. First, his own posture: batach, to lean his full weight upon Yahweh. Second, God's covenantal quality: chesed, the loyal love that does not revoke its pledge. Neither alone is sufficient in the psalm's logic. Trust without chesed would be faith without a reliable object. Chesed without trust would be provision the king never appropriates. Together they produce the verdict: 'he will not be shaken' (bal mot). The same pairing — human trust plus divine chesed — appears across the Psalter as the definition of covenant security (Ps. 13:5; 31:14; 32:10). Charles Spurgeon (The Treasury of David) calls v. 7 'the key to the whole psalm': 'The secret of the king's strength is the secret of every believer's strength — he hangs upon the arm of the Almighty.'"
