        "excerpt": "O LORD, in Your strength the king will be glad, and in Your salvation how greatly he will rejoice!",
        "body": "The psalm opens mid-celebration. The king's gladness has a specific object — 'Your strength' and 'Your salvation' — not his own resources. This is not a rhetorical flourish; it is a theological claim that frames everything that follows. The king's glory is derivative. The verbs in vv. 2-6 are all past-tense or perfect-tense, cataloguing what God has already done: given the heart's desire, refused to withhold the lips' request, met the king with blessings, set the crown, given life, bestowed splendor and majesty, made him most blessed forever, and made him joyful in His presence. The accumulation creates the effect of sheer abundance — the king is not missing a single thing that a covenant God could give.\n\nThe mention of the crown of fine gold (v. 3) is the psalm's most concrete image of royal investiture. In ancient Near Eastern culture, the crown was the symbol of divine appointment — the gods crowned the king, not the other way around. Israel's theology was distinct: Yahweh alone crowns, and the crown signals that this king rules under divine authority, not by divine nature (which was the Egyptian and Mesopotamian claim). When Psalm 21 says 'You set a crown of fine gold on his head,' it is making a theological point: royal authority is given, not inherent.\n\nVerse 4 introduces the psalm's exegetical tension. The king asked for life, and God gave it — 'length of days forever and ever.' Derek Kidner observes that this language was conventionally applied to the reigning king in ancient Near Eastern treaty and royal texts as a wish for long life, but that Israel's psalms consistently press such language past its conventional meaning toward eschatological depth. No Israelite king lived forever. The language either hyperbolizes dynastic hope, or it points beyond the current king to the One in whom all royal hope is concentrated. The New Testament chooses the latter reading: the risen Christ is the King who actually received 'life' in answer to His prayer (John 17:1-5; Hebrews 5:7) and holds that life 'forever and ever' (Revelation 1:18).\n\nVerse 6 is the summit of the retrospective: 'You make him joyful with gladness in Your presence.' The word for presence (*paneh*, face) will reappear in v. 9 as the face of divine wrath that destroys the enemies. The same divine presence that is the king's highest joy is the enemies' greatest terror. This structural repetition of *paneh* is one of the psalm's most sophisticated theological moves — God's face is not neutral; it either blesses or judges, depending on the posture of the one before it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yeshuah* (salvation, vv. 1, 5) shares its root with the name Yeshua/Jesus. *Atarah* (crown, v. 3) is the word for a queen's or king's ceremonial crown, distinct from *nezer* (the sacred diadem of the high priest). *Berakhah* (blessing, vv. 3, 6) is the covenant-blessing word that echoes the Abrahamic promise (Genesis 12:2-3). *Paneh* (presence/face, v. 6) sets up the deliberate echo in v. 9."
